post_text: The Food Services Department of FUHSD is thrilled to receive a grant from GENYOUth, a non profit dedicated to creating healthier school communities! GENYOUTH, along with it's private and public partners, raised funds for schools and we are grateful to receive the gift of $14,000. This grant will be used to help provide food for students and families during the COVID-19 crisis. Thanks to everyone involved in this effort and initiative to fight food insecurity during the pandemic and beyond!

post_text: Join us for a listening session on public safety with the City of Sunnyvale, Sunnyvale Public Safety and the Sunnyvale School District on Wednesday, July 22! Register at sunnyvale.ca.gov/unity.
shared_text:
City of Sunnyvale, California (Government)
July 16 at 1:15 AM ·

Our next listening series session "Dialogue with Youth: Public Safety and Schools" is on July 22. We hope you'll join us.

For the latest updates subscribe to the Sunnyvale Unity mailing list at Sunnyvale.ca.gov/subscribe

Wednesday, July 22
5:30 p.m.- 7:30 p.m.
ℹ️: https://sunnyvale.ca.gov/unity

featuring Fremont Union High School District, Sunnyvale School District, Youth Public Policy Institute, Sunnyvale Department of Public Safety and the City of Sunnyvale, California (Government).

About the sessions:
We are hosting a series of listening sessions to better understand community concerns. Our first General Listening Session centered around equity and inclusion, systemic racism, and police use of force was on June 25. The youth session will focus on the partnership between Sunnyvale schools and the Department of Public Safety.

Your support and engagement are vital as we find a path forward. Together we can make our city a safe and vibrant place for everyone.

The Homestead High School PTSA invites all FUHSD students to participate in a Personal Insight Questions Workshop with UC Davis Admissions Officer Melanie David! The workshop will take place on Wednesday, July 22 at 2 p.m. and is targeted to rising seniors.

Ms. David works for UC Davis Undergraduate Admissions and has been with the department for six and a half years. She has been the Bay Area Regional Representative for the last three years. This event will focus on how to write the Personal Insight Questions that are part of the UC application.

Register now to reserve your spot: https://ua.ucdavis.edu/register/?id=8a866fab-310a-4733-80b8-01f41df3607c

shared_text:
City of Cupertino - City Hall
June 29 at 10:49 AM ·

Community Forum on Policing, Part 2: Discussion with CUSD and FUHSD Students and Alumni
July 8, 2020, from 5:30 to 7:00 p.m.
Register at https://cityofcupertino.zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_m7sT1qAmSUCsHjQPY76E_g

The City of Cupertino is hosting a meeting in collaboration with the Fremont Union High School District, Cupertino Union School District, and Santa Clara County Sheriff's Office-West Valley Division regarding policing in Cupertino. The City, FUHSD, CUSD, and Sheriff's Office have received inquiries about policies and training regarding use of force, as well as the purpose of School Resource Officers.

The event will be hosted by City Manager Deborah Feng and include Superintendent Polly Bove, Interim Superintendent Stacy McAfee-Yao, Deputy Superintendent Graham Clark, and Captain Ricardo Urena. FUHSD and CUSD students and alumni are invited to this meeting to ask questions and express their opinions.

post_text: The cancellation of the Instrumental Music Awards didn’t stop Fremont High School teacher and Band Director Joe Kelly and FHS parents from recognizing our seniors. Since they couldn’t decorate the theatre and celebrate the seniors in person, three band families created 45 gift baskets that Joe and his family delivered to the seniors. Congratulations to the graduating seniors and thank you to the band program for going out of their way to recognize them! We love all the creative ways our staff and parents have found to continue to honor our graduates!
text: The cancellation of the Instrumental Music Awards didn’t stop Fremont High School teacher and Band Director Joe Kelly and FHS parents from recognizing our seniors. Since they couldn’t decorate the theatre and celebrate the seniors in person, three band families created 45 gift baskets that Joe and his family delivered to the seniors. Congratulations to the graduating seniors and thank you to the band program for going out of their way to recognize them! We love all the creative ways our staff and parents have found to continue to honor our graduates!

• State of the Admissions Nation due to COVID
• Navigating the College Search (from a distance) to Create a Financial Fit List of the Admissions Nation due to COVID
• Creative Summer Planning + Creating an Impact When You Can’t Go Outside
• Character Counts: How Character Plays a Powerful Role in Selective College Admissions State of the Admissions Nation due to COVID

We are hopeful that these webinars will answer many of the questions you have about the college admissions process and how to navigate it in this challenging time.

Register at go.collegewise.com/fremontunionwebinars.

post_text: Congrats to Tino's own Mr. Williams, who was honored with the Woodie Flowers Finalist Award at the virtual FIRST Regional Awards Show earlier this month. This award recognizes robotics mentors who inspire their students and teams to be their very best. Way to go Mr. Williams!
shared_text:
Cupertino Robotics
May 2 at 6:32 PM ·

We are beyond excited that our lead mentor, Mr. Williams, was presented with the Woodie Flowers Finalist Award for the San Francisco Regional! This award was announced at the virtual FIRST Regional Awards Show this past week, and recognizes mentors who best lead, inspire, teach, and empower their team.

We are so thankful for everything that Mr. Williams has done for our team and all of the students at Cupertino Robotics. His dedication and enthusiasm has pushed us to grow and learn in ways we could've never imagined, and he is truly an inspiration to us all.

Congratulations, Mr. Williams! 💖

If you'd like to read the nomination essay we submitted for the award, it can be found on our website at http://www.cupertinorobotics.org/blogs/williamsaward.

post_text:
We are thrilled to share that Google has generously donated $90,000 worth of meals from Moffett Park area restaurants and retailers to the FUHSD food service program as part of the new Sunnyvale Cares program. This donation to our meal program has allowed us to provide 10,000 high-quality, nutritious meals to those students that have been negatively impacted by the current coronavirus crisis.

The entire FUHSD team is grateful for community partners like Google who are working to help ease the burden on our families hit hardest by this pandemic. We are strongest when we work together in partnership to take care of one another. Thank you to Google for supporting us in this challenging time!
shared_text:
City of Sunnyvale, California (Government)
May 7 at 2:26 PM ·

⛑️Introducing Sunnyvale Cares, help for those that work so hard to help all of us.

🏪 Sunnyvale small businesses and nonprofits are the heart of our City. Through this new initiative, they will have access to almost $3 million to help with financial impacts caused by the COVID-19 pandemic. Sunnyvale Cares is made possible through a combination of City funds and private donations from Google, LinkedIn, Intuitive Foundation, and Jay Paul Company.

ℹ️ Read more about Sunnyvale Cares: https://sunnyvale.ca.gov/civicax/filebank/blobdload.aspx?BlobID=27047

• Support nonprofits and small businesses with a donation
• Learn more about the program
• Apply to receive funding (application and process will be posted later in May)

Leadership Opportunities in S.T.E.A.M.

The Cupertino Library Foundation Teen Advisory Council is looking for student leaders passionate about promoting S.T.E.A.M. (Science, Technology, Engineering, Art, Math.)

For the past 9 years we have been organizing Super Summer Science Search (S4) science competition for middle schoolers, and Gateway to Learning, a hands-on exhibit for the Cupertino Library Foundation showcasing S.T.E.A.M.

If you are interested in organizing these events with like-minded FUHSD students, and are looking for an opportunity to enhance your leadership skills, the Teen Advisory Council is looking for students like you.

We are recruiting committed members, incoming freshmen or older, interested in working with a dynamic team this summer. If this sounds like you, please fill out the application form for the Teen Advisory Council by May 15th, 2020. https://forms.gle/MN1RNeKLL94idTRe8

post_text: Congratulations to Lynbrook High School student Catherine Huang, selected as one of 621 semifinalists for the 2020 U.S. Presidential Scholars competition! Catherine has won first prizes and top awards at numerous international piano competitions and performed as a soloist with multiple orchestras. She is a California Young Artists Guild member and a 2019 YoungArts Gold Award Winner in Classical Music. Catherine is passionate about musical outreach; as Vice President of Lynbrook Music for Community she organized a benefit concert raising over $4,000 to aid victims of the California wildfires. Catherine will be studying applied math at Harvard University in the Fall.

Congratulations to outstanding Lynbrook High School student Allison Li, who was awarded the Joyce Ridgway Scholarship by the Central Coast Section (CCS)! Allison is a four-year scholar-athlete whose varsity sports career includes water polo, swimming and basketball.

Lynbrook Athletic Director Jennifer Griffin said, "Allison is very loyal to her teammates. To her, they have become a 'smaller community or family during my high school years.' This is something I want for all of the student athletes on my campus."

Joyce Ridgway served as a leader in the development of women’s sports in the CCS and the CIF. Due to her tireless determination and dedication to enhance and expand the opportunities for girls in sport, a $500 scholarship is offered annually to a deserving female high school senior who exemplifies the characteristics of leadership, self-sacrifice and integrity that is reflective of Joyce Ridgway’s character and contributions.

post_text:
Congratulations to Fremont High School student Melissa Lee, named Scholar-Athlete of the Year for the Santa Clara Valley Athletic League! Melissa is a decorated wrestler (two-time CCS Champion, two-time CIF All-State, Pan America Silver Medalist and six-time USA Wrestling California State Champion) and a member of the track and field team.

Fremont Athletic Director Jason Townsend shared that “Melissa started her “Yes We Can” program last summer as a way to inspire young girls to wrestle in a traditionally male dominated sport. Melissa chose to cut back her summer wrestling schedule so that she could get her initiative off the ground more quickly. This selflessness shows what a special person Melissa is and that she sees a larger purpose can be had through her athletic success.”

Each year, the Central Coast Section (CCS) honors fourteen students with Scholar-Athlete Scholarships. These exceptional student-athletes are nominated by their schools and put forth to their leagues for selection, with each honoree receiving a $500 scholarship. Way to go Melissa, you make us #FUHSDstrong!

post_text:
We are thrilled to announce that our Post-Secondary Academic Community Transition Program has been chosen as one of five Glenn Hoffmann Award Winners for 2020! The Hoffmann awards are given by the Santa Clara County School Boards Association to celebrate school and school district programs that significantly impact student success in our region.

Our Post-Secondary Academic Community Transition Program provides students with developmental disabilities with rich, community-based opportunities for growth and development. With the support of our highly trained staff, post-secondary students acquire social skills, explore their vocational interests, develop employable skills and flourish as members of the broader community.

In the photos here, students proudly participate in one of several student-run businesses, Creating Artistic Rewarding Designs by Students (CARDS), that are a vital part of the core curriculum in our post-secondary programs.

Congratulations to Homestead High School students Arnuv Tandon and Arnav Kulkarni whose project RemoteTA was one of 89 winners in the #BuildforCOVID19 Hackathon!

RemoteTA is an online volunteering platform allowing high school students to remotely volunteer with elementary school teachers and help teachers create the digital resources needed to teach online during COVID-19 school closures. Students act as “remote teacher’s assistants," helping teachers complete various online projects.

Hosted by the WHO, Google, Microsoft and other prominent tech companies, the hackathon provided an opportunity for developers around the world to come together and tackle challenges related to the coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic. Way to go Arnuv and Arnav, you make us #FUHSDstrong!

UPDATE ON CHANGES FOR SCHOOL MEALS

Beginning April 6, the following changes will be implemented to our school meal program during the closures:

· Due to demand, the District will be closing the Lynbrook and Monta Vista locations, with our other four locations continuing to serve meals (Fremont, Homestead, Cupertino and Fair Oaks Park).
· Meals will be served three days a week - Monday, Wednesday and Friday. This will reduce the number of trips required to receive meals.
· Each day we will provide two days’ worth of meals.

Meal service will also continue over Spring Break (week of April 12).

post_text:
Based on the current and best information we have today, and in partnership with the Santa Clara County Public Health Department and the Santa Clara County Office of Education, we have decided to close schools to students for three weeks beginning Tuesday, March 17 through Friday, April 3. Monday, March 16, was already scheduled as a non-instructional day for all FUHSD schools. During this three-week period, instruction will continue for our students, with staff providing lessons and assignments through our online tools, including School Loop, Schoology and Google Classroom.

Schools are an essential service and crucial to our communities, and the decision to close all Santa Clara County schools was not taken lightly. We are facing an unprecedented health crisis in our community, and new information is surfacing rapidly. It is likely our community will be seeing many more cases of COVID-19 in the coming weeks and months.

For more information, please read our full message at www.fuhsd.org.

post_text:
Monta Vista teacher and National Geographic Educator of the Year Kavita Gupta continues to inspire the next generation -

"To build an equitable future in STEM and to create a world that better caters to women, it is critical to nurture our female talent by providing relatable role models. As Marian Wright Edelman famously said, "You cannot be who you cannot see." I hope my female students see themselves in me, as a woman, immigrant, and mother, and believe that they too can make an impact in STEM fields."

post_text: Congratulations to Fremont High School senior Aryia Dattamajumdar who was awarded the prestigious Davidson Fellowship for Engineering! Aryia is the first student from Fremont High School to be awarded the Davidson Fellowship, which is given to students 18 and under who have completed a significant piece of work in the areas of science, technology, engineering, mathematics, literature, music or philosophy. Aryia was honored in Washington, D.C. last month.

post_text:
Congratulations to superstar Cupertino High School teacher Jenny Padgett, who was selected by the Lighthouse Guild as their Teacher of the Year for 2019! Dedicated to addressing and preventing vision loss, the Lighthouse Guild recognizes the powerful role teachers play in motivating students who are blind by recognizing a teacher each year based on nominations received directly from students.

Jenny's student nominee, Gene Kim, said, "Mrs. Padgett was my Honors American Literature teacher during eleventh grade, and she remains one of the most academically and socially influential teachers in my life. She listened and engaged with me as a unique individual, not just 'that blind student I see in the mornings everyday.'" Way to go Jenny, you make us #FUHSDstrong!

post_text:
Congratulations to superstar Cupertino High School teacher Sean Bui, selected as the Fremont Union High School District Teacher of the Year for 2019!

Sean was chosen for this honor because he strives to create a supportive and inclusive culture on the CHS campus, whether that means designing activities to help ELD students feel more at home or working with struggling students to relieve stress and have fun. His colleagues say he has a bubbly personality, demonstrates joy in the teaching profession and is a positive force for good in the world.

Each year, the Santa Clara County Office of Education recognizes an exceptional teacher from each of the more than 30 school districts in the county at the annual Teacher Recognition Celebration. This Fall, Sean will be honored and celebrated by his family, friends and colleagues as our district’s Teacher of the Year at the 50th Annual Teacher Recognition Celebration.

post_text: Congratulations to the incredible Cupertino High School students who received a perfect score on the AP Computer Science A Exam for 2018! Way to go Anjan Bharadwaj, Justin Du, Olivia Du, Abhinav Gokhale, Matthew Guan, Bidipta Sarkar, Ishika Shah and Ling Wong, eight of the 193 students around the world to receive a perfect score.

post_text:
Interested in learning more about the Next Generation Science Standards and the type of lessons our students are engaging in every day in the classroom?

Current parents of Fremont and Homestead High School students are invited to attend our first FUHSD Parent Science Engagement Night on April 30 at Fremont High School (a second Parent Science Engagement Night will be held on May 15 for parents of current Cupertino, Lynbrook and Monta Vista students).

Learn more and register today at https://bit.ly/2G8vUqh.

post_text: Join us for the annual FUHSD Art Showcase! Art created by students from each of our five high schools will be displayed at the FUHSD Adult School (located at Vallco Mall) from April 15 through May 17. Our student artists will be honored at a special reception on April 25.

post_text:
Don't forget to join us this Thursday, April 4 for our next Board Office Hours session at Fremont High School! The session will take place from 6 to 7:30 p.m. in the Fair Oaks Room in the new main office building located on Fremont Ave. (Building A) with trustees Naomi Nakano-Matsumoto and Jeff Moe.

This program provides community members with the opportunity to find out more about the work of the Board and District, ask questions and provide valuable feedback. Please visit the Board Office Hours webpage for more information.

post_text: Join us for a special presentation on parenting in the age of social media on April 9 from 6:30 to 8 p.m. at Fremont High School. Co-sponsored by My Digital TAT2, this event will cover topics including managing your digital reputation, cyberbullying and engaging your teens in constructive conversation around social media.
